Appendix A: Sensitivity Analysis and Theoretical Robustness of the Toy Model

This appendix provides a mathematical analysis of the 2D toy model introduced in §3.5, focusing on the theoretical properties assumed in the main text. No numerical simulations are performed; instead, we derive bounds that guarantee the desired behavior under parameter uncertainty.

A.1 Model Equations and Parameter Domain

The toy model is

\begin{aligned}
\dot{I} &= -a I + b (1 - C) + d_1 + g_1 u, \\
\dot{C} &= -c C - k \cdot \operatorname{sat}(I) + d_2 + g_2 u,
\end{aligned}

with \operatorname{sat}(I) = \max(-I_{\max}, \min(I, I_{\max})), I_{\max}>0. The parameters satisfy

a,b,c,k,g_1,g_2 > 0, \quad a,c \in [a_{\min}, a_{\max}],\; b \in [b_{\min}, b_{\max}],\; k \in [k_{\min}, k_{\max}].

The disturbances d_1,d_2 are bounded: |d_1| \le D_1, |d_2| \le D_2. The control u is bounded by the consent set.

A.2 Contractivity of the Uncontrolled Dynamics

For u=0 and d_1=d_2=0, the system is piecewise linear. We analyze the contraction properties using a Riemannian metric. Choose a metric M = \operatorname{diag}(1, \rho) with \rho>0 to be determined. The generalized Jacobian in the unsaturated region (|I|<I_{\max}) is

\tilde{J} = M J + J^\top M = \begin{pmatrix}
-2a & -b - \rho k \\
-b - \rho k & -2c\rho
\end{pmatrix}.

\tilde{J} is negative definite if and only if its leading principal minors are positive: -2a < 0 (true) and

\det(\tilde{J}) = 4ac\rho - (b + \rho k)^2 > 0.

This is a quadratic inequality in \rho: k^2 \rho^2 + (2bk - 4ac)\rho + b^2 < 0. A necessary and sufficient condition for existence of \rho>0 satisfying this is that the discriminant be positive and the quadratic have a positive root. The discriminant is

\Delta = (2bk - 4ac)^2 - 4k^2 b^2 = 16ac(ac - bk).

Thus, a positive \rho exists iff ac > bk. When this holds, any \rho in the interval between the two positive roots makes \tilde{J} negative definite, implying contraction with rate \lambda = \min\{a, c\rho\} in the metric M.

In the saturated region (|I| = I_{\max}), \operatorname{sat}'(I)=0, so the Jacobian becomes diagonal with eigenvalues -a and -c, hence trivially contracting. Therefore, if ac > bk holds for the nominal parameters, the system is contracting on the whole state space. If this inequality does not hold globally, contraction can still be established over the bounded domain because the state remains within a compact set, and the system may spend only limited time in the region where the metric condition fails. In that case, the existence of a common Lyapunov function (e.g., V = I^2 + \rho C^2) can be verified by bounding the worst‑case growth and using the fact that the state is bounded. The same approach applies when disturbances are present: contraction is preserved with a reduced rate [Wang & Slotine, 2005].

A.3 CLF Candidate and Fading Control

A natural CLF candidate is V(I,C) = \frac{1}{2}(I^2 + \rho C^2). Its derivative along the controlled dynamics is

\dot{V} = I\dot{I} + \rho C\dot{C} = -a I^2 - c\rho C^2 - b I(1-C) - \rho k C \operatorname{sat}(I) + (g_1 I + \rho g_2 C) u + I d_1 + \rho C d_2.

Using the bounds |I| \le I_{\max}, |C| \le C_{\max} (which can be derived from the dynamics), we obtain

\dot{V} \le -\alpha V + \beta_1 \|d\| + \beta_2 \|u\|

for some \alpha,\beta_1,\beta_2>0. The CLF feedback is chosen as u = -\gamma (g_1 I + \rho g_2 C) with \gamma sufficiently large to dominate the drift and disturbances. The fading factor \kappa(V) ensures that when V is small, u is scaled down, and eventually u \to 0.

A.4 Robustness to Parameter Variations

The stability analysis is robust to bounded parameter variations because the CLF decrease condition can be rewritten as

\dot{V} \le -\alpha_0 V + \delta_{\text{param}} V + \beta_1 \|d\| + \beta_2 \|u\|,

where \delta_{\text{param}} captures the deviation from nominal parameters. As long as \alpha_0 > \delta_{\text{param}}, the system remains stable. This condition can be satisfied by choosing the nominal CLF with a sufficient margin, or by adaptively adjusting the feedback gain. Thus, the theoretical guarantees hold for all parameters within a neighborhood of the nominal values.

