Appendix B: Robustness of Delay Embedding to Noise – Theoretical Bounds

This appendix provides the theoretical justification for the reconstruction error bound used in the main text.

B.1 Setting

Let \mathbf{x}_t be the state on a compact manifold \mathcal{X} \subset \mathbb{R}^n evolving according to \dot{\mathbf{x}} = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x}). The observation is y_t = h(\mathbf{x}_t) + v_t, where h: \mathcal{X} \to \mathbb{R} is a smooth generic observation function, and the noise satisfies |v_t| \le \eta for all t.

Define the delay map \Phi: \mathcal{X} \to \mathbb{R}^d by

\Phi(\mathbf{x}) = \bigl( h(\mathbf{x}), h(\phi_{-\tau}(\mathbf{x})), \dots, h(\phi_{-(d-1)\tau}(\mathbf{x})) \bigr)^\top,

with d \ge 2n+1 and \tau>0 generic. Takens’ theorem states that \Phi is a diffeomorphism onto its image.

B.2 Reconstruction Error Bound

Let \mathbf{d}_t = (y_t, y_{t-\tau}, \dots, y_{t-(d-1)\tau})^\top be the noisy delay vector. Define the reconstruction \hat{\mathbf{x}}_t = \Phi^{-1}(\mathbf{d}_t) (the pre‑image under the embedding). Because \Phi^{-1} is Lipschitz on the compact set \Phi(\mathcal{X}) (as it is a diffeomorphism between compact manifolds), there exists a constant L_\Phi such that

\|\hat{\mathbf{x}}_t - \mathbf{x}_t\| \le L_\Phi \|\mathbf{d}_t - \Phi(\mathbf{x}_t)\|.

Now \mathbf{d}_t - \Phi(\mathbf{x}_t) = (v_t, v_{t-\tau}, \dots, v_{t-(d-1)\tau})^\top, so its norm is at most \sqrt{d}\,\eta. Therefore

\|\hat{\mathbf{x}}_t - \mathbf{x}_t\| \le L_\Phi \sqrt{d}\,\eta.

Thus the reconstruction error is bounded by a constant times the noise amplitude.

B.3 Effect on the Estimated Dynamics

The estimated state evolves according to \hat{\mathbf{x}}_{t+1} = \Phi^{-1}(F_{\text{obs}}(\mathbf{d}_t)), where F_{\text{obs}} is the map induced by the dynamics on the delay coordinates. By the Lipschitz property of \Phi^{-1} and the smoothness of the dynamics, the error in the estimated dynamics is also O(\eta). This ensures that the closed‑loop analysis with estimation error \delta = L_\Phi \sqrt{d}\,\eta is valid.

