Appendix C: Proofs of Auxiliary Lemmas

C.1 Lemma 4.1 (Reversibility)

Lemma. Under Assumption 4.1 (contractivity of free dynamics), for any initial condition \mathbf{x}_0 and any time T, if \mathbf{u}(t)=0 for t \ge T, then there exist constants k,\lambda>0 such that

\operatorname{dist}(\mathbf{x}(t), \mathcal{A}) \le k e^{-\lambda (t-T)} \operatorname{dist}(\mathbf{x}(T), \mathcal{A}),

where \mathcal{A} is the unique attractor of \dot{\mathbf{x}} = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x},0).

Proof. By definition of contraction, there exists a metric M(\mathbf{x}) and a rate \lambda > 0 such that for any two trajectories \mathbf{x}(t) and \mathbf{y}(t) of the unperturbed system, the distance measured in that metric decays as e^{-\lambda t}. Let \mathbf{y}(t) be the trajectory that lies on the attractor \mathcal{A} and satisfies \mathbf{y}(T) = \arg\min_{\mathbf{a} \in \mathcal{A}} \|\mathbf{x}(T) - \mathbf{a}\|_M (the projection onto the attractor). Since \mathcal{A} is invariant, \mathbf{y}(t) \in \mathcal{A} for all t. Then

\operatorname{dist}_M(\mathbf{x}(t), \mathcal{A}) \le \|\mathbf{x}(t) - \mathbf{y}(t)\|_M \le e^{-\lambda (t-T)} \|\mathbf{x}(T) - \mathbf{y}(T)\|_M = e^{-\lambda (t-T)} \operatorname{dist}_M(\mathbf{x}(T), \mathcal{A}).

Because all norms on a compact set are equivalent, there exists a constant k such that the Euclidean distance satisfies the same inequality with possibly a different k. For the perturbed system with bounded \mathbf{d}, the same exponential convergence holds with a slightly reduced rate; see [Wang & Slotine, 2005] for the proof. ∎

C.2 Feasibility of the QP (Lemma from §5.4)

Lemma. For any \mathbf{u}_{\text{RL}}, if there exists a \mathbf{u} that satisfies the CLF constraint and the fairness CBF constraint, and if 0 \in \mathcal{U}_{\text{consent}}(t), then the QP is feasible. Moreover, if the constraints are inconsistent, introducing a slack variable for the CLF constraint with a sufficiently large penalty ensures feasibility.

Proof. The set \mathcal{U}_{\text{consent}}(t) is convex and contains 0. The CLF constraint is linear in \mathbf{u}: \nabla V^\top \mathbf{g} \mathbf{u} \le b_{\text{clf}}, where b_{\text{clf}} = -\alpha V + \beta\|\mathbf{d}\| - \nabla V^\top \mathbf{f}. The fairness CBF constraint is also linear: \nabla B_{\text{fair}}^\top \mathbf{g} \mathbf{u} \ge b_{\text{fair}}. The intersection of these two half‑spaces with \mathcal{U}_{\text{consent}}(t) is convex. By assumption, this intersection is non‑empty, so the QP has a solution (the projection of \mathbf{u}_{\text{RL}} onto a non‑empty convex set). If the intersection is empty, we replace the CLF constraint with \nabla V^\top \mathbf{g} \mathbf{u} \le b_{\text{clf}} + \varepsilon, where \varepsilon is a slack variable penalized in the objective. By making \varepsilon sufficiently large, the relaxed constraint is always feasible, and the penalty ensures that \varepsilon is small when the original constraints are nearly satisfied. ∎

C.3 Theorem 6.2 (Stability under Switching)

Theorem. Assume that for each mode i there exists a CLF V_i such that \dot{V}_i \le -\alpha_i V_i + \beta_i \|\mathbf{d}\|. Suppose there exist constants \mu \ge 1 and \lambda > 0 such that for any two modes i,j, V_i(\mathbf{x}) \le \mu V_j(\mathbf{x}) for all \mathbf{x}. If the switching signal \sigma(t) has average dwell‑time \tau_a > \frac{\ln \mu}{\lambda} where \lambda = \min_i \alpha_i, then the switched system is iISS and the convergence results of Theorem 6.1 hold.

Proof. Define W(t) = V_{\sigma(t)}(\mathbf{x}(t)). Between switches, \dot{W} \le -\lambda W + \beta\|\mathbf{d}\| with \beta = \max_i \beta_i. At a switching time t_k from mode i to j, we have W(t_k^+) = V_j(\mathbf{x}(t_k)) \le \mu V_i(\mathbf{x}(t_k)) = \mu W(t_k^-). For any t > 0, let N(t) be the number of switches in [0,t]. Then by the comparison lemma,

W(t) \le \mu^{N(t)} e^{-\lambda t} W(0) + \int_0^t \mu^{N(t) - N(s)} e^{-\lambda (t-s)} \beta \|\mathbf{d}(s)\| ds.

The average dwell‑time condition implies N(t) \le N_0 + t/\tau_a for some N_0. Then \mu^{N(t)} \le \mu^{N_0} e^{(\ln \mu / \tau_a) t}. Choosing \tau_a > \ln \mu / \lambda gives \lambda - \ln \mu / \tau_a > 0. Hence the first term decays exponentially, and the second term is bounded by a convolution with an exponential kernel, establishing iISS. Once the state is near \mathcal{M}_{\text{self-reg}}, the CLF becomes small and the control fades; the free dynamics then drive the state to the attractor as in Theorem 6.1. ∎

